That is why I am so proud that, together with the pattern of occasional rights, John Lewis, I can introduce a law strengthening the position of employees.
This groundbreaking legislation will give workers the same legal opportunities to prevent discrimination in unions, as in other forms of discrimination - and stop anti-union forces
Modify the Labour Relations Act to allow all employees who face discrimination if they want to join trade unions, to sue in a civil court – and to sue compensation or compensation – an initiative is correct and necessary.
But it's certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by U.S. standards.
The best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and other petitioners put forward in the law is to reconnect the American ideal.
Despite the trade union struggles that have taken place in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states - Americans once supported countries around the world to embrace, expand and respect labor rights.
There was a time, and millions of Americans still remember them when the country in one breath promoted democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to assembly.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his advisers supported the country to adopt a constitution designed to ensure that the military autocracy of Hideki Toja would be replaced by democracy.
They were convinced that employees and their unions played a role in the formation of a new Japan, included in them the language and openly acknowledged that "the right of employees to gather, collectively negotiate and act is guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his advisers urged the Germans to form a constitution to ensure that Adolf Hitler's fascism would be replaced by a strong democracy.
The Germans realized that employees would need to organize and promote themselves in the new nation, and therefore included a clause that openly says: “The right to create associations that will secure and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every individual and every profession or profession.
The arrangements that will restrict this right or seek to be damaged will be annulled. Measures to fulfil such a purpose are illegal.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt chaired the International Human Rights Commission, which proposed the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which was adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a global treaty, the petitioners and Roosevelt included in it a guarantee that “everyone has the right to create and enter unions in order to protect their interests.”
Americans have accepted the fundamental premise for generations that labour rights are human rights.
When the country advised other countries on how to create a civil and democratic society, the Americans explained that the right to create labor unions - and their participation in collective bargaining with firms and government agencies in the position of an equal partner - must be protected.
Now that these rights are being invaded in America, it is definitely necessary to return to the American ideal that working people must have the right to organize and promote themselves in a free and open society.
As the reverend Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Today, everyone knows that the unions have not diminished the power of the nation, but expanded it.
They have increased the standard of living of millions of people, creating a market for industry, and have led production to an unsuspected level.
Those who attack the unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History does not forget, and we should not.
Formal recognition of labour rights as human - and extending civil rights protection to prevent discrimination in the organisation of trade unions - is delayed.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are renewing the ideals that have raised America and made it a real promise of democracy.
Judge temporarily blocks law that could shut down all Louisiana abortion clinics
A federal judge on Sunday temporarily blocked the Louisiana law, which lawyers say would likely shut down all five clinics performing abortions in the state.
The order enacted by the signature of Louisiana Governor Bobby Jindal in June, which is due to come into force on September 1, would require doctors carrying out abortions to have the right to accept a patient in a hospital, 30 miles from the practice.
The judge's order means that doctors can temporarily continue to carry out legal abortions and, in the meantime, they have to obtain this permission.
"The proposing party will be able to legally operate and, in the meantime, obtain permission," federal judge John deGravelles' order reads.
The hearing will be scheduled within a month so that the judge can issue a more permanent order concerning the law.
Activists for the rights to abortion resolution, which is the last in a series of similar measures, welcomed and said that it would give doctors more time to get permission.
“Today’s decision ensures that women in Louisiana are safe from a tricky law to deprive them of health and their rights,” said Nancy Northup, president and executive director of the Centre for Reproductive Rights, who, on behalf of three of the five clinics, has sought the law’s blocking of the law.
It was not immediately clear whether the decision also applied to doctors from two clinics who were not among the plaintiffs, and also applied for this permit.
Louisiana is among the eleven states that passed similar laws, with the courts in Alabama and Mississippi declaring such measures unconstitutional.
Key parts of the Texas law that would close most of the remaining clinics in the state were blocked by federal judges on Friday.
Women's rights activists to abortion, along with the Association of U.S. obstetricians and gynecologists and the U.S. Medical Association, argue that the need to have this permit puts demands on doctors that are not necessary from a medical point of view.
Opponents of abortion countered that the measures aim to protect women's health, and some also welcomed the fact that the clinics would be closed because of the measures.
The Center for Reproductive Rights said only one doctor performing abortions has permission in Louisiana.
If all doctors in the state were forced to stop performing miscarriages, this doctor would also stop performing the procedure out of fear for his safety, the group said.
