How many dimensions can our universe have?
The idea that our universe may have more than three spatial dimensions may sound foolish, fantastic, strange or mystical.
Yet it is concrete and completely acceptable.
To understand this, let us avert our eyes from the universe as a whole for a while to something more grounded, specifically a long and thin garden hose for watering.
Imagine that you stretch the hundred-meter garden hose from one side of the canyon to the other and watch the whole scenery from a half-kilometer distance (as in the picture and on the next page).
From such a distance, you can easily record a long in a horizontal direction of a stretched hose, but if you do not suffer from austrosightedness, you can hardly recognize the thickness of the hose.
Given its great distance from the hose, you would think that an ant forced to live on a hose has only one dimension in which to walk: the left-right dimension along the hose.
When someone asks you where the ant was at the moment, you answer them with just one indication: the distance of the ant from the left (or right) end of the hose.
All we want to say is that from a half-kilometer distance a long piece of hose looks like a one-dimensional object.
In the real world, the hose has a thickness.
If we enlarge everything, we will suddenly see the second dimension - in the shape of a circle-wracking hose.
In such an enlarged view, it is clear that the ant can actually move in two independent dimensions: in the already well-known left-right dimension along the length of the hose, but also in the "dimension in/anti-clockwise movement", that is, around the circular cross-section of the hose.
You begin to understand that to determine the position of a small ant you have to enter two numbers: how far it is from the end of the hose and where there is a wrapping hose on the circle.
This reflects the fact that the surface of the hose is two-dimensional (note. Experts will point out that this chapter focuses purely on the disorder theory of strings.
Chapter 12 and 13 discusses the indisturbance aspects.)
The surface of the hose is two-dimensional: one long long longitudinal dimension is represented by a direct arrow, the dimension in the direction of the circumference, marked with a circular arrow, is short and coiled.
However, there is a clear difference between these two dimensions.
The size along the hose is long and easily visible.
The size of the wrapped circuit of the hose is short, "rolled" and harder to notice.
To realize the existence of a circular dimension, we had to examine the hose with significantly better resolution.
This example illustrates the important feature of spatial dimensions.
That they are divided into two groups.
They can be either large, vast, and therefore directly noticeable, or, on the contrary, small, coiled and much less observable.
Of course, in this case, we did not exactly avoid being able to reveal the "saint" dimension of the hose-covering thickness.
