Kaluza justified his radical claims by providing an elegant and persuasive framework in which Einstein's general relativity and Maxwell's electromagnetic theory can be woven into a single, unified conceptuality structure.
Immediately, the question arises as to how this observation of Kaluz goes together with the obvious fact that we see exactly three dimensions of space.
The answer, which Kaluza quietly assumed between the lines and which was clearly expressed and clareded by the Swedish mathematician Oskar Klein in 1926, stands and falls with the assertion that the spatial geometry of our universe can have both large and shrewd dimensions.
This means that, like the dimension in the direction of the hose length, our universe has a large, vast and lightly visible three dimensions, the existence of which we realize every moment.
But analogically with the circular circumference of the garden hose, the universe can have additional dimensions, firmly coiled into space so tiny that they have so far remained hidden even from our most perfect experimental apparatuses.
