Genetic disorders are often misdiagnosed
A woman from Britain describes how she thought she would die after a bad diagnosis for many years.
After being diagnosed with another disease, Karin Rodgers spent most of her adolescence thinking she had only a few years left to live.
In fact, it was Charcot-Marie-Tooth syndrome (CMT) - a group of hereditary disorders that damage nerves outside the brain and spine.
The CMT UK charity organization said that a bad diagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT, because very little is known about the disease.
Approximately 23 000 people are believed to suffer CMT in the UK, which can be manifested in motor skills such as muscle weakness, clumsy gait and twisted toes.
In the case of those affected, numbness or pain may also occur, this condition is incurable and progressive, which means that over time the symptoms worsen.
When Rodgers was thirteen, she thought she was suffering from Freidreich ataxia (FA) - a disease that had a very poor prognosis.
She believed that before she celebrated her 18th birthday, she would be confiscated into a wheelchair, and she was dead before she was thirty.
The mother of two, who is now 51, says: "As a child, I knew that I can't do the same things as the others.
I fell down every day and it took me longer.
I could never ride roller skates or skateboards with other kids, and at school I was bullied because of the way I used to walk and run.”
When Rodgers was thirteen and she was after several surgeries to release her Achilles tendon and straighten her feet, she took advantage of the fact that her doctor had left the room, and peered into her dossing where she learned that she was suffering from the FA.
“I felt guilty because I was snooping, so I didn’t tell anyone, but when I got home, I looked up information about the disease in the library and wrote to the FA Association,” he says.
When they answered me, I was shocked, I was absolutely panicked.
I thought that before I was eighteen, I would end up in a wheelchair, and before I was twenty-five, I would be dead, and in the meantime, I would gradually lose all my powers.
I was all alone and I was planning a funeral.”
When she was seventeen, she realized that her ability to walk hadn't deteriorated as much as she had anticipated, and she asked her surgeon about it.
He just stood up, hugged her and said, "Gold, I don't think you have the disease, or you'd be in a wheelchair.
I think it will be something much less dangerous to life.”
After undergoing several genetic tests, it was discovered that he had CMT.
"When he explained to me what CMT was, I thought I was a child of fortune," she said.
